<h1>To Charles West</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Mount Vernon June 6th 1769</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>As you did not come down to our April Court according to promise, or according to your own expectation, I shoud be glad to know if you have considerd anything further of the matter I mentiond to you at your own House.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>The Slipe of Land which I then proposd to buy, is in my opinion, the most indifferent part of your Tract,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> because one half of it is cold wet ground, and the other half stony Hill sides; but as it lyes upon my Line, and is pretty well stockd (that is the Wood part of it) with Rail Timber, it woud answer the end for which I want it, as well as betterNor woud my purchase of this small piece injure the Sale, or settlement of the residue, as you may see by the Plat Inclosd, which leaves the remainder in a very pretty figure and mostly upon the Hills where the Level and tendable Land chiefly lyes for I woud take it in a long Square
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-08-02-pb-0209">[209]</span>
from the Creek to Mr Russells Line adjoining my own, and either 60, 70, or 80 rod wide as you yourself might choose.</p>
<p>For this piece I woud pay you ready money, and as a security against any consequences which might result from Mr Russells claim (under old Robt Johnson) I woud take a Bond from you to refund me the neat sum which I shd pay in case of a recovery (which is putting it upon the most favourable Issue imaginable for you as few others I presume woud take any thing less than a general Warrantee) by which means you woud have the use of my Money whilst I had the use of your Land and I am much mistaken if the Interest of it is not more than an equivalent for the Rent of the Loggd Cabin below the Hill.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>I send this Letter up on purpose in hopes that you will favour me with a definitive answer because I have just come to a resolution of rebuilding my Mill, &amp; fitting her for Mercht Work and till the Mill wright comes up to lay of the spot to fix her in (which will be on thursday or friday next from Fredericksburg Fair) I do not know but there may be a more convenient place found by drawing the water from my present Pond along a Race to a spot on the Creek so near to your Line as to be incommoded by it<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0004-ptr">4</a>for this Reason therefore and for the sake of Rail Timber more convenient than I at present have it I am inclind to make what I think a generous offer at once for this slipe of Land and that is a pistole an Acrethis sum when compard with the Landwhen compard with the times, for let it be rememberd, that the Scarcity of our Money at this juncture is such, as to have raisd it in value almost equal to Sterling, whereas at the time Doctr Cockburne inclind to buy the Land,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> he coud have paid a hundd pound Curry with about 60 Sterg, &amp; now I cannot do it with 80 Sterg which makes a very material difference, &amp; causd me to add as above, that this price compard with the Land and the times, must be tht a very gen[erou]s offer.</p>
<p>Perhaps you may imagine by my wanting to hurry you into an answer, that I have heard of some other Person or Persons who may want to buy it, and woud give this or a greater price; but you may rely upon it, when I assure you upon my word and honour that I know of no such thing further than you yourself mentioned to meI have no other Reasons for applying to you at this time than what I have candidly declardon the contrary, I do know, that it is a general receivd opinion that there never will
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-08-02-pb-0210">[210]</span>
be the same price offered for the Land again, which Doctr Cockburn talkd of giving for it in order to get fixd in this neighbourhoodfor I know that that was his motive for offering such a price, and the Reason why I have straind the point is to see if the matter can be brought to a conclusion at once as it is not worth my while in so trifling a purchase as 70, 80, or an 100 Acres to be hegling for a few pounds. I am Sir, Yr Very Hble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0146-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Book ]">ALB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>GW spent the night of 23 Mar. at Charles Wests ordinary in Loudoun County at the junction of the Colchester and Carolina roads near present-day Aldie.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Charles West owned a 484acre Tract of Land in Fairfax County lying on Doeg [Dogue] Creek adjoining the Lands of the Honble George Wm Fairfax, the said George Washington and others. Nothing came of GWs proposal to buy a Slipe of this land, but on 28 May 1772 West agreed to sell the entire tract, sometimes called the Chapel Lands. On 28 Oct. 1772 he deeded the land to GW, for which GW was to pay West 605 current money. The agreement is in GWs hand and signed by him and West. It is on deposit at <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Morristown National Historical Park, Morristown, N.J. [[former abbreviation: NjMoHP]] ]">NjMoHP</span>. A copy of the deed, also in GWs hand, is in the library at Mount Vernon. Typescripts of both are in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ In-house collection on CD-ROM at Papers of George Washington, Univ. of Virginia; documents to be merged into PGWDE in future. ]">CD-ROM:GW</span>. GWs bond to West, dated 28 Oct. 1772, for the third and final payment of 202.10 for the land is privately owned. The final payment due on 25 Nov. 1774 was made on 30 Nov. 1774.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>The agreement of 28 May 1772 between West and GW provided: George Washington doth moreover agree to be at one half the cost and charge of defending the Title to this Land in case a Suit, which is threatned by James Russell Esqr. of London, or his agent or attorney here, should think proper to commence one. James Russell (17081788), formerly of Maryland, was a prominent London merchant engaged in the tobacco trade. He may have been a relation of Anthony Russell, who in 1758 bought land adjoining Wests. Both tracts of land were part of a large grant made to William Travers in 1678. Robert Johnston (Johnson), who died c.1768, had been administrator of the estate of John Brown (died c.1744). Brown had willed the 484acre tract to his daughter, Ann, wife of Charles West.<span class="choice deletion" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Deleted: 'Robert Johnston, Brown's administrator, may or may not be the Robert Johnston of Frederick County who died in 1764.' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2006-06-12]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"><img alt="deletion" src="images/deletion_mark-trans.png" style="border:none;vertical-align: text-bottom; padding-right:2px"/></span> For later letters concerning the West-Russell land dispute, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0211" class="document">George William Fairfax to GW, 12 Mar. 1770</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0281" class="document">William Carr to GW, 17 Dec. 1770</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0004">4</a>
 
   <p>GWs mill on Dogue Run had been destroyed or damaged several times as far back at least as March 1760 (see especially <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Donald Jackson and Dorothy Twohig, eds. &lt;i&gt;The Diaries of George Washington&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Charlottesville, Va., 197679. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Diaries</span></span>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-01-01-02-0005-0003#GEWN-01-01-02-pb-0254" class="document">1:254</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-01-02-02-0003-0012#GEWN-01-02-02-pb-0057" class="document">2:57</a>), and he had come to a decision by the spring of 1769 to build a new and larger mill. On 22 Mar. 1770 GW fixed the site of his new mill on Dogue Run near where the road from Gum Spring to Colchester crossed the creek. For an account of
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-08-02-pb-0211">[211]</span>
  the construction of the mill, see especially <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Donald Jackson and Dorothy Twohig, eds. &lt;i&gt;The Diaries of George Washington&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Charlottesville, Va., 197679. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Diaries</span></span>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-01-02-02-0005-0006" class="document">2:218</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-01-02-02-0005-0006#GEWN-01-02-02-pb-0222" class="document">222</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-01-02-02-0005-0011" class="document">23234</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-01-02-02-0005-0014" class="document">24345</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-01-02-02-0005-0036" class="document">335</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0146-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0123&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-08-02-0123-fn-0009#GEWN-02-08-02-0123-fn-0009" class="document">Robert Stewart to GW, 25 Jan. 1769, n.9</a>.</p>

</div>
